    <h1>BIG PIC&#xAD;TURE Like rid&#xAD;ing a train into a kalei&#xAD;do&#xAD;scope</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201028/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-10-28"><time>2020-10-28</time></a>
        - <span>OPINION</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>With its psychedeli­c light show, the Bund Sight­see­ing Tun­nel is one of Shang­hai’s top tourist des­ti­na­tions.</p>
    <p>In the heart of the Chi­nese city’s water­front area, the tun­nel runs across the Huangpu River, tak­ing rid­ers from the Bund to Lu­ji­azui.</p>
    <p>But this five-minute trip is not like any other train ride.</p>
    <p>The trip, in an au­to­mated rail car, fea­tures var­i­ous au­dio-vis­ual ef­fects.</p>
    <p>The tun­nel is cov­ered in puls­ing lights, which are ac­com­pa­nied by an omi­nous sound­track.</p>

